Sass-Compatibility was a reference site that listed differences between Sass implementations — Ruby Sass and LibSass, but also gaps between Ruby Sass releases such as 3.2 versus 3.3 or 3.4. It grew out of a GitHub gist, then a styled CodePen, before becoming a standalone project aimed at teams deciding whether a LibSass migration was realistic for their codebase.

{% callout "warning" %}
**Disclaimer:** The project is **defunct.** Ruby Sass reached its end-of-life
status, Dart Sass replaced it, LibSass is likewise unmaintained, and the tooling
described below has long been superseded by the aligned behavior modern
compilers provide today. Treat this page as historical context.
{% endcallout %}

## What it offered

You could skim a compatibility matrix instead of auditing your entire codebase by hand: missing features or subtle semantic differences surfaced as labelled checks, so you knew what you might lose (or gain) when switching engines.

## How it worked (at the time)

Early versions relied on tedious manual SassMeister runs and hand-maintained tables. [Valérian Galliat](https://twitter.com/valeriangalliat) helped move that to automation built around [sass-spec](https://github.com/sass/sass-spec), the engine compliance suite — even though sass-spec itself was messy in spots (mixed eras of tests, some LibSass-only cases, disabled cases).

Whenever a gap had no upstream test, new coverage was contributed to sass-spec where possible, or authored specifically for Sass-Compatibility until the ambition was “only sass-spec-derived tests everywhere.” A Rake task iterated tests, delegated evaluation to SassMeister’s backend, then emitted YAML consumed by the Jekyll site to render green/red support cells—see [the archived sources](https://github.com/sass-compatibility/sass-compatibility.github.io).

